Practice Problems — Topic 9
Q1. Topology identification: for each application, identify the most appropriate isolated topology and give the primary reason:
(a) 5W wireless charging receiver, Li-ion battery output (3.7-4.2V), USB 5V input
(b) 3kW solar inverter DC-DC stage, V_PV=300-600V input, V_DC_bus=800V output
(c) 200W 48V telecom to 12V/16.7A converter
(d) 15W isolated auxiliary supply for a motor drive control board, 540V DC bus input, 15V output
(e) 100kW EV fast charger DC-DC stage, V_in=800V grid-tied DC bus, V_out=200-1000V (variable battery)
Q2. Quantitative comparison — flyback vs forward at 80W:
V_in=48V DC, V_out=12V, I_load=6.67A, f_s=200kHz.
For flyback: n=0.3, D=0.43, L_m=150µH, I_peak=4.8A (primary), I_s_peak=16A (secondary).
For forward: Ns/Np=0.3, D=0.40, V_secondary=14.4V, output inductor.
(a) Flyback secondary peak current vs forward secondary peak current (I_forward_s_peak ≈ I_load + ΔI_L/2 = 7A). Why is flyback secondary peak current so much higher?
(b) Secondary diode average current: flyback (I_D_avg = I_load = 6.67A) vs forward (I_D1_avg = D×I_load, I_D2_avg = (1-D)×I_load). What is peak diode current for each?
(c) Output capacitor ripple: flyback (C_out must supply all load during ON period — ΔV = I_load×D/(C×f_s)) vs forward (ΔV = ΔI_L/(8×f_s×C) with L_out=22µH). For C=220µF, ΔI_L=1.5A: calculate ΔV for each topology.
(d) Which output capacitor value would be needed for flyback to achieve the same 50mV ripple as the forward converter with its 220µF cap?
(e) Conclusion: at 80W with 48V input, which topology is more appropriate for a product requiring tight 12V output regulation? Justify with your calculations.
Q3. Power level boundaries — when to upgrade topology:
A product family uses flyback converters throughout. Engineering is asked whether each new product should use flyback or switch topology.
(a) 120W version: peak primary current with flyback at V_in=100V, D=0.45: I_peak = 2×P_in/(V_in×D) where P_in=120/0.80. Is this achievable with standard MOSFETs?
(b) 200W version: same calculation. At what peak current does the flyback become impractical (hint: consider transformer size and MOSFET I_FSM ratings)?
(c) For the 200W version: calculate what D and peak current a forward converter would use (same V_in=100V, V_out=12V, assume D=0.40). Compare to flyback.
(d) Cost trade-off: flyback at 200W requires 1 MOSFET, 1 diode, no output inductor. Forward requires 1 MOSFET, 2 diodes (D1+D2), 1 output inductor, 1 reset winding. At what power level does the efficiency improvement of forward converter justify the extra component cost?
(e) A rule of thumb used in industry is "flyback below 100W, forward above 100W for single-output offline converters." Does your analysis support this rule? What factors might cause a designer to deviate from it?
Q4. LLC vs phase-shift full-bridge selection:
A 1kW, 48V output power supply from a 390V DC bus (post-PFC). Target efficiency ≥ 96% at 50% load.
LLC option: f_r=200kHz, ZVS and ZCS, estimated efficiency 97% at 50% load, narrow input range ±15%.
Phase-shift full-bridge: f_s=100kHz, ZVS at full load (loses ZVS below 30% load), estimated efficiency 95.5% at 50% load, handles ±30% input variation.
(a) Both achieve ≥ 96% target — which additional criterion would determine the choice?
(b) If the application requires the converter to regulate over a ±25% input voltage range: which topology is more suitable?
(c) At 10% load (100W): LLC uses burst mode (switching stops periodically). Phase-shift full-bridge loses ZVS. Which has better light-load efficiency and why?
(d) EMI comparison: LLC switches at variable frequency 150-300kHz (frequency dithering inherent). Phase-shift full-bridge switches at fixed 100kHz. Which is easier to pass conducted EMI limits? Why?
(e) Final decision: for a server power supply where efficiency at 50% load is paramount and input voltage variation is only ±10% (from a well-regulated PFC stage): which topology would you choose? Justify with at least three specific reasons from (a)-(d).
Q5. Complete topology selection and justification report:
You are the lead power electronics engineer at a company designing three new products simultaneously. For each product, state: (1) topology chosen, (2) three specific technical reasons, (3) one key challenge to address in the design.
(a) Product 1: IoT sensor node power supply. V_in=5V USB, V_out=3.3V/100mA isolated (for noise immunity). P_out=330mW. Cost budget extremely tight (< $0.50 for power stage components).
(b) Product 2: Industrial motor drive auxiliary supply. V_in=540V DC bus, V_out=24V/2A (48W) for control board. Must survive V_in surges to 800V. High reliability required.
(c) Product 3: Data centre server power supply unit. V_in=90-264V AC, V_out=12V/125A (1500W). Must achieve 80 PLUS Titanium (>91% at 50% load, >94% at 100% load). High volume production.
